summary: This document is a US Department of Justice foreign travel questionnaire for an Assistant US Attorney (AUSA) from the Southern District of New York (SDNY) traveling to Stockholm, Sweden in February 2020. The purpose of the trip is to interview and debrief a witness (Jane Doe) in the ongoing, sensitive investigation into Jeffrey Epstein, with Ghislaine Maxwell identified as a subject of the investigation.

persons.name: Jeffrey Epstein
persons.context: Named as the subject of the case ('In re Jeffrey Epstein') for which the official travel is being conducted.

persons.name: Ghislaine Maxwell
persons.context: Identified as a subject of the investigation, believed to be a citizen of the US, UK, and France.

persons.name: Jane Doe
persons.context: A Swedish national listed as the person to be interviewed and debriefed during the official travel to Stockholm.

connections.description: Both are named as subjects of the same ongoing, sensitive investigation by the USAO-SDNY.
Maxwell is a subject of the investigation for which Jane Doe is being interviewed as a witness.

events.title: AUSA Travel to Sweden for Witness Interview
events.description: An AUSA from the USAO-SDNY departs New York for Stockholm, Sweden, to interview and debrief a witness in the Jeffrey Epstein investigation.

events.title: Completion of High Threat Security Overseas Seminar
events.description: The traveling AUSA successfully completed the HT401 High Threat Security Overseas Seminar, as evidenced by an attached certificate.

locations: Sheraton Stockholm Hotel, Tegelbacken 6-Box 195, Stockholm SE 10123, Sweden
keyFacts: In February 2020, a US Attorney from SDNY traveled to Stockholm, Sweden on official business to interview a witness ('Jane Doe') in the Jeffrey Epstein investigation.
The document explicitly names Ghislaine Maxwell as a subject of the same ongoing and 'very sensitive' investigation.
The travel was approved and coordinated through official DOJ channels, indicating the continued active investigation into Epstein and Maxwell after Epstein's death.
Foreign authorities (presumably Swedish) had cleared the visit and were prepared to cooperate with the US investigation.
The traveler's security clearance level is listed as Top Secret.
